{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524048"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:01:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:01:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13950"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13950"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.03,0.06,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110422"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6580"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13950"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92686"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"260"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41670"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110422"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is admitted to the hospital ward with worsening pain and swelling in her right knee. You are called as the duty intern to assess her. She has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis (RA), type 2 diabetes, and hypertension. Her medications include methotrexate, hydroxychloroquine, metformin, and irbesartan. For RA flares previously she has used prednisolone with good effect, with the most recent prednisolone course complete two months ago. She reports that while all her joints are somewhat painful, her right knee has become significantly worse over the past two days, with increasing swelling, warmth, and inability to bear weight after going for a big shopping spree with her granddaughter. She denies any recent trauma or injections to the knee.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 102/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Her right knee is markedly swollen, warm, and tender to touch with a moderate effusion. There is a severely reduced range of motion due to pain. Other joints show mild synovitis consistent with her known RA. Initial blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 15.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 12.8 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (2.0-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 380 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 85 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 120 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate: 65 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perform joint aspiration of the right knee","Start intravenous methylprednisolone","Administer intra-articular corticosteroid injection","Commence oral antibiotics","Urgent rheumatology consultation prior to any intervention"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management for this patient is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eperform joint aspiration of the right knee\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient presents with symptoms and signs highly suspicious for septic arthritis, which is a medical emergency requiring prompt diagnosis and treatment to prevent joint destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral factors in this case raise the suspicion for septic arthritis:\u003Cbr /\u003E1. The patient has rheumatoid arthritis (RA), which is a risk factor for septic arthritis. \u003Cbr /\u003E2. She has several immunosuppressive risk factors, which can predispose to joint infection, including an underlying diagnosis of diabetes, and immunosuppressive medications (methotrexate and hydroxychloroquine) for her RA.\u003Cbr /\u003E3. While she has general joint pain from her RA, the right knee is inflamed out of proportion to the other joints.\u003Cbr /\u003E4. She has systemic symptoms including fever, tachycardia, and appearing unwell.\u003Cbr /\u003E5. The affected joint is swollen, warm, and very painful, with a reduced range of motion.\u003Cbr /\u003E6. Her blood tests show elevated inflammatory markers (white cell count, neutrophilia, and C-reactive protein) which, while non-specific, support the possibility of an acute infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting intravenous methylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if this was a flare of rheumatoid arthritis without suspicion of infection. However, this option could be dangerous if septic arthritis is present, as it may mask symptoms and allow the infection to worsen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing oral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E without first confirming the diagnosis and obtaining synovial fluid for culture would be premature. While antibiotics will likely be needed if septic arthritis is confirmed, it\u0027s crucial to obtain samples for microbiological analysis before starting antimicrobial therapy and intravenous therapy is likely to be more appropriate in any case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intra-articular corticosteroid injection\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated if there is any suspicion of joint infection. Injecting steroids into an infected joint can worsen the infection and lead to devastating consequences including rapid joint destruction. This would be an appropriate treatment for a non-infectious RA flare affecting a single joint, but not in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent rheumatology consultation prior to any intervention\u003C/strong\u003E would delay the diagnosis and treatment of potential septic arthritis. While rheumatology input is valuable in managing RA, in this emergency situation, joint aspiration should not be delayed. The duty team should proceed with joint aspiration and then involve appropriate specialists based on the results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJoint aspiration will allow for synovial fluid analysis, including cell count, Gram stain, culture, and crystal analysis. This is crucial for diagnosing septic arthritis and guiding appropriate antibiotic therapy. If septic arthritis is confirmed, the patient will require urgent orthopaedic consultation for joint washout, in addition to intravenous antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with rheumatoid arthritis, a single joint that is inflamed out of proportion to other joints should raise suspicion for septic arthritis.","Septic arthritis is a medical emergency requiring prompt diagnosis and treatment to prevent joint destruction.","Risk factors for septic arthritis include advanced age, diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis, prosthetic joints, recent joint surgery, and immunosuppressive medications."],"references":["Kherani RB, Shojania K. Septic arthritis in patients with pre-existing inflammatory arthritis. CMAJ. 2007 May 22;176(11):1605-8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1867838/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92686"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13950"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92686"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-31T00:39:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-31T00:40:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6580"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110422"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data"